In FY 2024‚Äì25 alone, the programme reached 3.05 lakh beneficiaries across 10 states, supporting children, adolescents, and mothers. With the support of 2,000+ Suposhan Sakhis and around 2000 nutrition champions, the BNF team has impacted over 1.5 lakh adolescents, 10000+ malnourished children and 13000+ mothers across more than 1700+ villages. Community ownership remains at the heart of BNF‚Äôs work.

We remain committed to strengthening this journey and continuing to work towards better nutrition for every community we serve.

I‚Äôm back ‚Äî after a much-needed pause to breathe, reflect, and reset. üíõ

After almost 6 months of stepping away, catching my breath, and finding space to think about what‚Äôs next after winding down the D2C product line ‚Äî I‚Äôm slowly making my way back.

This pause helped me reconnect with why I started Archana‚Äôs Kitchen in the first place ‚Äî to make everyday cooking simpler, more joyful, and less stressful for home cooks like you.

The mission still remains: To make it easy for anyone to cook delicious, wholesome meals at home.

author: Gulzar Singh
post_text:
Dahi Suran Ki Sabzi ‚Äî a simple, comforting dish that reminds me how the most humble ingredients can create the most satisfying meals üíõ

I love pairing this with hot phulkas, an Andhra-style Palakaru Vepudu (a vibrant spinach stir fry), and a kala chana salad for a colourful, protein-rich, and wholesome thali-style meal üåøüåà

Below are the link to the recipes
Dahi Suran Sabzi - https://www.archanaskitchen.com/dahi-suran-ki-sabzi-recipe-stir-fried-yam-in-dry-yogurt-curry-recipe

Andhra Style Palakaru Vepadu - https://www.archanaskitchen.com/andhra-style-palakaru-vepadu-recipe-spinach-stir-fry-recipe

Kala Chana Salad - https://www.archanaskitchen.com/indian-style-black-chickpea-salad-recipe

Phulka - https://www.archanaskitchen.com/phulka-roti-chapati-puffed-indian-bread

üì¶ Lunchbox Tip:
Dahi Suran Ki Sabzi packs beautifully in a lunchbox ‚Äî just make sure to cool it slightly before sealing to avoid curdling. Pair it with phulkas and a dry sabzi like Palakaru Vepudu for a mess-free and balanced lunch.

üç± Portion Control Tip:
A small katori of suran sabzi + 1 phulka + 1 ladle of chana salad + a scoop of stir-fried greens = a meal that‚Äôs filling, nutritious, and easy on the tummy. Perfect for everyday lunches!

Let me know if you‚Äôve tried suran before or if this recipe tempts you to give it a go ‚ú®

author: Kwanele Langa
post_text:
Beef & Cheese Pies 

Ingredients
 ‚Ä¢ 500 g ground beef
 ‚Ä¢ 1 large onion, finely chopped
 ‚Ä¢ 1 large potato, grated
 ‚Ä¢ 1 large carrot, grated
 ‚Ä¢ 2 garlic cloves, minced
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp garlic powder
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp onion powder
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp salt
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp paprika
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp Italian herbs
 ‚Ä¢ 1 tsp all-purpose spice
 ‚Ä¢ 2 beef stock cubes
 ‚Ä¢ ¬Ω tbsp flour
 ‚Ä¢ 2 tbsp tomato paste
 ‚Ä¢ Puff pastry
 ‚Ä¢ Grated cheese
 ‚Ä¢ 1 egg, beaten (for egg wash)

Method
 1. In a bowl, combine ground beef, onion, potato, carrot, salt, and all spices. Mix well and marinate for 30 minutes.
 2. Heat oil in a pan over medium heat. Saut√© garlic until fragrant.
 3. Add the beef mixture and cook for 5 minutes, stirring.
 4. Stir in tomato paste, stock cubes, flour, and a little water. Cover and simmer for 7 minutes until thick.
 5. Allow filling to cool slightly.
 6. Cut puff pastry, add filling and cheese, seal, and brush with egg wash.
 7. Bake at 200¬∞C for 20‚Äì25 minutes or until golden and crisp.

author: Ayasha golpo
post_text:
Omelette Sandwich Recipe 

 Ingredients:
For the Omelette:
3‚Äì4 eggs
2 tbsp milk (optional ‚Äì for fluffiness)
Salt to taste
1 onion (finely chopped)
1 green chilli (finely chopped)
2 tbsp chopped coriander
2 tbsp chopped capsicum or tomato (optional)
1‚Äì2 tsp oil or butter

For the Filling:

Bread slices (white, brown or sandwich bread) ‚Äì 4 to 6
Butter or mayonnaise ‚Äì as needed
Cheese slices or grated cheese ‚Äì optional
Cooked chicken, veggies or aloo stuffing ‚Äì optional

 Method:

1. Prepare the Omelette Base:

Crack eggs into a bowl, add salt, milk, onion, chilli, coriander, capsicum/tomato.

Beat well.

2. Cook the Omelette:

Heat a non-stick pan and grease it with a little oil or butter.

Pour a portion of the egg mixture and spread it evenly.

Quickly place 1‚Äì2 bread slices on top of the uncooked egg (press lightly so they stick).

3. Flip the Sandwich:

Once the egg is cooked and firm, gently flip the whole thing.

Now, spread some butter or mayo over the bread side facing up.

Add cheese or stuffing of your choice in the center of the bread.

4. Fold & Toast:

Fold the edges of the omelette over the bread to seal like a parcel.

Toast on low flame until the bread is golden and crispy.

5. Cut & Serve:

Remove and cut into squares or triangles.

Serve hot with ketchup or chutney.

 Variations:

Add cooked keema, saut√©ed veggies, or even potato masala inside.

Sprinkle some chili flakes and oregano for a pizza twist.

Photo by Mousumi

author: Mousumi Khatun
post_text:
Macher Jhol (Bengali Fish Curry)

Fish
Rohu / Katla / Rui ‚Äì 4‚Äì5 pieces
Turmeric ‚Äì ¬Ω tsp
Salt ‚Äì to taste
Mustard oil ‚Äì for frying
For Jhol (Gravy)
Mustard oil ‚Äì 3 tbsp
Bay leaf ‚Äì 1
Dry red chilli ‚Äì 1
Potatoes ‚Äì 2 medium (cut into wedges)
Green chillies ‚Äì 2 (slit)
Ginger paste ‚Äì 1 tsp
Spices
Turmeric ‚Äì ¬Ω tsp
Kashmiri chilli powder ‚Äì 1 tsp
Coriander powder ‚Äì 1 tsp
Cumin powder ‚Äì ¬Ω tsp
Salt ‚Äì to taste

Method
Marinate fish with turmeric & salt. Shallow fry in mustard oil till lightly golden. Remove and keep aside.
In same oil add bay leaf & dry red chilli.
Add potatoes, fry till edges turn golden.
Add ginger paste, saut√© lightly.
Add all dry spices + salt, mix well.
Add hot water (thin gravy). Bring to boil.
Add green chillies, simmer till potatoes are cooked.
Gently slide in fish pieces.
Cook on low heat 5‚Äì7 minutes.
Switch off ‚Äî no garam masala, no coriander (authentic Bengali touch).

author: James Dupree
post_text:
Coca-Cola has been a beloved beverage for decades, but the truth behind its effects on health is alarming. Beyond quenching thirst, it has a surprising number of cleaning and industrial uses. From loosening rusted bolts to stripping corrosion off metal, Coca-Cola has been a go-to for various maintenance tasks. Its acidic nature makes it highly effective in cleaning applications, which should make us question what it does to our insides.

The consumption of sugary drinks, like Coca-Cola, is linked to several health problems, such as obesity, type 2 diabetes, and heart disease. Despite its enticing taste, Coca-Cola offers no nutritional value and has the potential to harm your gut, teeth, and overall health in the long run. Many of us consume it casually, unaware of the dangers it poses.

It‚Äôs time to make better beverage choices. Water, herbal teas, or naturally sweetened drinks provide hydration without the damaging effects of sugary sodas. Take control of your health by eliminating or reducing such beverages from your daily routine.

author: Elvia Cabrera
post_text: (2/3) ‚ÄúI knew nothing about gardening. But I knew how to google, so I looked up some easy stuff to plant. Turns out it‚Äôs hard to mess up herbs. So I went to the clearance rack at Home Depot and got some herbs. All of the soil was contaminated, so I backed up a dump truck full of organic soil. Nevaeh‚Äôs kindergarten class came out and planted the first seedlings. There wasn‚Äôt much structure in the beginning. A lot of times I‚Äôd just sit around with the kids and look at clouds. But over time the garden became a sort of outdoor science classroom. All of us were learning together. If something died, we‚Äôd just try a new spot. We learned about worms, and lady bugs, and praying mantises. Then we learned about food systems. I couldn‚Äôt help but notice the diets of these kids: all sugar and processed food. Some of them couldn‚Äôt name a single vegetable. But how could you blame them? There are 55 fast food restaurants in this community, but not a single supermarket. So we started growing vegetables in our garden. Not all of the kids were into it. But in every class there would be two or three‚Äî who were always around, and involved. Nevaeh was one of those kids. She came to all the camps. She came on the nature walks. She just stuck to me. At first her mother was skeptical, but she could see the consistency. And soon she was bringing Nevaeh to work with me in the garden on weekends. In the beginning Nevaeh was sorta quiet, and off to the side. But over time she took ownership of the garden. Those became her plants, not mine. Whenever volunteers came to help with composting-- Nevaeh would take the lead. And if you were doing it wrong, she‚Äôd grab that rake right out of your hands. Ten years have passed since we planted that first garden. And Harlem Grown has expanded to 12 different urban farms. 6,000 lbs of organically grown products have been given to the community free of charge. But the plants are just a byproduct. We‚Äôre trying to grow healthy children. But not just children. All of us are learning together. Today our most important employee is Nevaeh‚Äôs mom. She‚Äôs learned more about gardening than any of us. And she‚Äôs the Agricultural Director of all our farms.‚Äù

author: Prearna's Creation
post_text:
Mutton Korma  ü•©

Ingredients :
500g Mutton
1.5 Onions
3tbsp Oil
Whole Spices (2 Cinnamon  Sticks, 5 Black Pepper Corns, 3 Green Cardamoms, 1 Black Cardamom, 3 Cloves)
1tbsp Ginger Garlic Paste
1/2tsp Turmeric Powder
1/2tbsp Red Chilli Powder
1/2tbsp Coriander Powder
1tsp Salt or as per taste
1.5 Cups Water
100g Curd (whisked)
1/4tsp Nutmeg Powder
1/4tsp Mace Powder
1/2tsp Kewra Water

Method :
1. Slice Onions thinly.
2. Deep fry onions till they turn light golden brown.
3. Remove on kitchen towel to drain out excess oil.
4. Grind fried onions coarsely.
5. Heat oil in a pressure cooker. Add whole spices. Saute for few seconds.
6. Add mutton and cook on high flame stirring continuosly for 3 - 4 mins.
7. Add ginger garlic paste. Cook for 1 - 2 mins on medium flame.
8. Add turmeric powder, red chilli powder and coriander powder. Mix well and cook till oil separates.
9. Add salt and water. Mix well. Bring to a boil.
10. Pressure cook and take 5 whistles.
11. Open lid and reduce excess water for 2 - 3 mins on high flame.
12. Lower the flame and add whisked curd. Mix well and cook for 2 - 3 mins.
13. Add ground birista (fried onions) and mix well. Cook till it turn a little thick and oil is separated.
14. Add nutmeg powder, mace powder and kewra water. Mix well and cook for 2 - 3 mins.
15. Serve with rice, roti or naan and Enjoy.
